    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1253855178" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1253855178" />
    <a title="Heather Brinkerhoff Burdsal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3946058-heather-brinkerhoff-burdsal"><img alt="Heather Brinkerhoff Burdsal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1510293061p2/3946058.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1253855178?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Heather Brinkerhoff Burdsal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Heather Brinkerhoff Burdsal" href="/user/show/3946058-heather-brinkerhoff-burdsal">Heather Brinkerhoff Burdsal</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1253855178" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6620484539647726752">Booooo! Slime! Filth! Muck! Rubbish! Boo! Boooo! Boooooooo!<br/><br/>I made it probably 80% of the way through this book before it came to a screeching halt.<br/><br/>The First 80%:<br/>Let&apos;s start by establishing that one sign of a terrible writer is that the book&apos;s characters seem like only a thin veil over the author&apos;s own personality. I didn&apos;t feel like I was reading a book, but rather seeing a weird look at the author&apos;s private thoughts. So now I know that Marcus Sakey has some serious incest pedophilia fantasies a</span>
  <span id="freeText6620484539647726752" style="display:none">Booooo! Slime! Filth! Muck! Rubbish! Boo! Boooo! Boooooooo!<br /><br />I made it probably 80% of the way through this book before it came to a screeching halt.<br /><br />The First 80%:<br />Let's start by establishing that one sign of a terrible writer is that the book's characters seem like only a thin veil over the author's own personality. I didn't feel like I was reading a book, but rather seeing a weird look at the author's private thoughts. So now I know that Marcus Sakey has some serious incest pedophilia fantasies and a bizarre fetish involving collar bones.<br /><br />Why I Stopped (Spoilers):<br />You can't have a plot that completely undermines the main tenets of the world you created. You just can't. Your readers will hate you. Coop's whole character hinges on the fact that he is a Brilliant with the ability to tell when someone is lying—when a person's body language is dissonant with their thoughts. Yet the Big Plot Twist is that he has been lied to every day for the past decade and manipulated into doing evil acts. HOW? Are you seriously telling me, after I have read hundreds of pages that depend on this man's super power as his driving force and main characterization, that his power somehow didn't function at the most crucial moments of his life? It's like saying, "At this critical juncture, Superman actually somehow was not super at all. There was no kryptonite or anything, he just wasn't super. And he didn't know he wasn't super at the time. Everyone just kind of forgot about the whole strength and flying and laser vision stuff. Then everything fell apart. PLOT TWIST! Yay, I'm an author, I'm so clever!"<br /><br />Bleck. Get it out of my brain! I never want to think about this ever again.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6620484539647726752" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


